The functional groups on the surface of carbon dots were characterized by FT-IR technique (Fig. 3
                        ). MA and TETA characteristic bands were observed similar to those in previous reports [30,31]. The FTIR spectrum of the carbon dots showed a characteristic broad vibration band of hydroxyl (O-H) and amine (N-H) groups at 3415 cm−1 
                        [32]. The vibration bands of C-O, alkenyl/carbonyl (C=C/C=O), and alkyl (C-H) stretching were observed at 1018, 1525–1730, and 2924 cm−1, respectively [33–35]. The presence of the vibration band at 1380 cm−1 was caused by C-H bending [36]. This FT-IR spectrum indicates abundant hydroxyl, alkenyl, carbonyl, and amino groups on the carbon dots. By comparing the FT-IR spectra, MA and TETA were completely transformed into carbon dots as signature signals of MA and TETA greatly diminished after the transformation.

The PMT residue was often found in a variety of fruits, vegetables, and water resources. In this work, apple, cucumber, and drinking water were chosen as real samples for investigating the accuracy and reliability of our sensing method. These three real samples were spiked with the standard PMT in four different concentrations (0.0, 10.0, 25.0, and 50.0 µM) and then the PMT was extracted and measured using HPLC and fluorescence techniques. According to HPLC chromatograms, the PMT from the standard solutions and extracted from the samples showed up at 2.98 min (Fig. 9
                        ). For both HPLC and fluorescence methods, the percentage recoveries were in the acceptable range of 98.6–107.1% and the relative standard deviation in percentage (%RSD) was lower than 1.2, indicating that our proposed method had excellent accuracy and reliability (Table 2
                        ). Moreover, the t-test and F-test were investigated and they showed no significant differences between both methods at a 95% confidence level. These results indicated that carbon dots could effectively detect PMT in apple, cucumber, and water samples with good accuracy and reliability.
